is is the name of a family descended from Hugh <i>Corbet</i>, a Norman baron who settled in Shropshire following the Norman Conquest. One of his descendants, Sir Richard Corbet, was granted land near Shrewsbury in 1223; since the 13th century, this place has been known as Moreton Corbet. The name was taken from Shropshire to Scotland in the 12th century and to northern Ireland in the 17th century, and thence to North America by at least one group of bearers of the name."],"variants":[{"name":"Corbit","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Corbett  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Corb","meanings":["English (Durham): nickname from Middle English <i>corb</i> ‘raven’ (from Old French <i>corb</i>; compare   Corbett  ,   Corbin  )."]},{"name":"Corbet","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Corbett  .","History: Walter Corbet, a royal knight in 12th-century Scotland, was the first of that name in that kingdom. His 13th-century descendants were major landholders in the Borders, and in the 14th century they acquired lands in the North of Scotland."]},{"name":"Corbitt","meanings":["English: variant of   Corbett  .","Irish: variant of   Corban  ."]},{"name":"Corban","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Corbáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Corbán</i>’ or <b>Ó Coirbín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Coirbín</i>’, both possibly from an occupational name based on <i>corb</i> ‘chariot’. Both names have also been Anglicized as   Corbett  .","Irish: alternatively, a variant of <b>Currivan</b>, from <b>Ó Coirbheáin</b>, itself a variant of   Corban   (pronounced with three syllables in Irish).","Romanian: nickname derived from <i>corb</i> ‘crow’, with the augmentative suffix <i>-an</i>."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Walter Corbett was born in 1300, in Alveston, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Peter de Corbet, was 26 and his mother, Ela de Audley, was 25."},"et":{"1300–Deceased":"1300–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1311–1361":"1311–1361","1313–1363":"1313–1363","1315–1383":"1315–1383","1355–Female":"1355–Surnud","1376–1395":"1376–1395","1275–1361":"1275–1361","1275–1360":"1275–1360","1275":"1275","1363":"1363","1395":"1395","1383":"1383","1361":"1361","1360":"1360","1315":"1315","1313":"1313","1300":"1300","1355":"1355","1311":"1311","1376":"1376","about 1310":"umbes 1310","Audley, Staffordshire, England":"Audley, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Alveston, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Alveston, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1300–Deceased":"1300–Kuollut","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1311–1361":"1311–1361","1313–1363":"1313–1363","1315–1383":"1315–1383","1355–Female":"1355–Kuollut","1376–1395":"1376–1395","1275–1361":"1275–1361","1275–1360":"1275–1360","1275":"1275","1363":"1363","1395":"1395","1383":"1383","1361":"1361","1360":"1360","1315":"1315","1313":"1313","1300":"1300","1355":"1355","1311":"1311","1376":"1376","about 1310":"noin 1310","Audley, Staffordshire, England":"Audley, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Alveston, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Alveston, Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1300–Deceased":"1300–Décédé","1300–Male":"1300–Décédé","1311–1361":"1311–1361","1313–1363":"1313–1363","1315–1383":"1315–1383","1355–Female":"1355–Décédée","